g and the means for the state to assert its legitimacy. The construction process-as well as Ethiopians' experience of living with the disruption of construction zones-reveals the tension and conflict between the promise of progress and the possibility of failure. Mains demonstrates how infrastructures as both ethnographic sites and as a means of theorizing such concepts as progress, development, and the state offer a valuable contrast to accounts of African abjection and decline.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Sep 2020) 0aCities and townszEthiopiaxGrowth. 0aCommunity developmentzEthiopiazĀwasa. 0aCommunity developmentzEthiopiazKefa Kifle Hāger. 0aCommunity developmentzEthiopiazKefa Kifle Hāger. 0aCommunity developmentzEthiopiazĀwasa. 0aEconomic development projectszEthiopiaxPlanning. 0aInfrastructure (Economics)zEthiopia. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK eBook-Package 2019z978311069632540uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781478007043zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781478007043423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781478007043.jpg  a978-3-11-069632-5  DUK eBook-Package 2019b2019  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles